SIMPLE: evaporate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evaporate
<hw>E*vap"o*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Evaporated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Evaporating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>evaporatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>evaporare</ets>; <ets>e</ets> out +
<ets>vapor</ets> steam or vapor. See <er>Vapor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To pass off in vapor, as a fluid; to escape and be dissipated,
either in visible vapor, or in particles too minute to be
visible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To escape or pass off without effect; to be
dissipated; to be wasted, <as>as, the spirit of a writer often
<ex>evaporates</ex> in the process of translation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To give moderate liberty for griefs and discontents to
<qex>evaporate</qex> . . . is a safe way.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evaporate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Evaporate
<hw>E*vap"o*rate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To convert from
a liquid or solid state into vapor (usually) by the agency of heat; to
dissipate in vapor or fumes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To expel moisture from (usually by means of
artificial heat), leaving the solid portion; to subject to evaporation;
<as>as, to <ex>evaporate</ex> apples</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To give vent to; to dissipate.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My lord of Essex <qex>evaporated</qex> his thoughts in a
sonnet.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Evaporating surface</b></col> <fld>(Steam Boilers)</fld>,
<cd>that part of the heating surface with which water is in
contact.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evaporate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Evaporate
<hw>E*vap"o*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>evaporatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety> <def>Dispersed in vapors.</def>
<rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>evaporated</ent>⟦br⟧
